  "prompt": "What are the legal precedents related to money laundering cases?",
  "response": "There are several important legal precedents related to money laundering cases. Some key examples include:\n\n1. United States v. Bank of New England (1985)\n- Established corporate criminal liability for willful failure to file suspicious activity reports\n\n2. United States v. BCCI Holdings (1991)\n- Major international case highlighting systematic money laundering practices\n- Resulted in significant penalties and restructuring of banking regulations\n\n3. Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) cases\n- Established reporting requirements for financial institutions\n- Created framework for detecting and preventing money laundering\n\n4. Proceeds of Crime Act (UK, 2002)\n- Expanded definition of money laundering\n- Introduced more comprehensive prosecution standards\n\n5. Basel Committee Guidelines\n- International standards for anti-money laundering compliance\n- Influenced legal frameworks globally\n\nThese precedents have shaped modern anti-money laundering legal approaches. However, I want to be transparent that legal details can be complex, and this overview is general in nature. For specific legal advice, consulting a qualified attorney is recommended.\n\nWould you like me to elaborate on any of these precedents?",
